    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-11-20T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-11-20T09:00:00-05:00" n="635"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d635">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/190: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-20T22:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 20, 1929—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 21—2:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1018. Local press today carries article, pertinent portions of which follow:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Determination to effect the abolition of extraterritoriality on January
                            1st next was reaffirmed by Dr. C. T. Wang, Monday<note n="24"
                                xml:id="d635fn24">November 18.</note> morning, according to Chinese
                            telegraphic advices from Nanking. Touching on the subject of
                            extraterritoriality, the Foreign Minister said that China was the only
                            country in the world where this archaic system prevailed, and that the
                            Chinese report says that the Nanking Government has decided not
                            recognize the rendition agreement which was negotiated by Dr. V. C. [<hi
                                rend="italic">K</hi>.] Ting and the foreign consuls in Shanghai in
                                1926<note n="25" xml:id="d635fn25">See <ref
                                    target="frus1926v01#pg_1023">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1926, vol. <hi
                                        rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 1023</ref> ff.</note> when
                            General Sun Chuan-fang was at the head of the Kiangsu provincial
                            government.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
